@gluap I'm no XML expert either, or Python expert for that matter.  After thinking some more on this, maybe additional levels of abstraction isn't the way to go. The trackpoint (and waypoint and routepoint) classes could have a (list of) TPX class that extends ElementTree to add hr, temp, etc. That way, all of the data would be stored in the ElementTree, upon read, and have access to all the standard ElementTree methods for any extension. Then you would have hr and temp attributes, populated during the parse, upon serialization it could put them back in to the ElementTree and just call the super's tostring() to handle the rest. The basic Garmin fields would probably cover 90% of the use cases, just like by Stava: https://strava.github.io/api/v3/uploads/

Should we add any supported schemas to the xsd folder to reference for documentation?

As far as implementation, I would use ElementTree from the standard library. It's been in since 2.5. The cElementTree module has been deprecated. The API should be the same as the lxml etree API for all reading and writing. The problem is that parser options are minidom and lxml. I don't think there is an easy way to use minidom to build an ElementTree. From what I can find online, the ElementTree and cElementTree modules both have better performance than minidom on most XML layouts. Maybe the library should dump minidom in favor of ElementTree completely? I might just be babbling at this point.

